review_blob: Hints of bread and caramel with some floral notes from the hops. Pours a cloudy amber color with lots of head. Very carbonated. Taste is cloyingly sweet and malty for a Saison, Alcohol is overbearing and hot tasting, some clove notes. Not my favorite Saison.
Pours bright with great head retention. Hints of citrus in the nose. Has strong Pine and Evergreen flavors with a crisp finish. Excellent beer for the style.

Moderate hints of Citrus and tangerine in the nose, very little head retention, The appearance is vibrant yellow in color and without haze which is not indicative of wheat beers. The mouthfeel reminds me of a Pilsner. The taste is overwhelmingly tangerine which is clearly from some artificial flavoring. Little to no malt presence. Overall, a pretty terrible beer.
Caramel notes aroma with a hint of ginger, brown color with a small amount of lacing. Medium body. Has some bitterness similar to a stout. The ginger flavor is apparent almost to a fault.

Pale straw in appearance, light body, strong citrus aroma with floral hints. Only a slight trace of head from a strong pour, bitterness all the way through.

Overall, a light bodied IPA that was good, but blends into the highly competitive style of IPAs.
Fleeting head, amber in color with an escaping bitterness and a mild kiwi aroma. Nothing is glaringly wrong with this beer but nothing stands out either. Expect it to be drinkable but unremarkable.

Mild hop aroma with a hint of copper. creamy blanket of head that stays firmly on top of the beer that does not dissipate. Hazy amber in color.

Expect some residual sweetness with medium body. Hop forward taste that goes a bit overboard on the IBUs. Expect a spicy bitterness that lingers. Not as balanced as some other DIPAs Ive tried. 

Overall, a decent DIPA that goes a bit overboard on the bitterness.
beer_name: Victory Hop Ranch Imperial India Pale Ale

review_blob: Bready, malty and thick. I taste a hint of chocolate but the caramel shines through the most. Little hop presence, malt aroma.

Strong hop aroma, cloudy amber colored appearance. Strong rye flavor balanced by West Coast hop bill. Strong velvet body from the rye is present, heavy lacing, moderate carbonation levels. Overall delicious, sets the bar for Rye IPAs.

Cloudy straw in appearance, medium hop presence, horse blanket aroma with a touch of funk. Heavily carbonated, with large bubbles that remain in the glass, some lacing. Bone dry with light body and a lingering fusel aftertaste.

A DIPA taken to the extreme. Even at 115 IBUs and 10.5% the beer was pleasantly balanced. Strong citrus aroma from the hops dominated from the first smell to the last taste. When poured the cloudy dark amber hue obfuscated the glass. Even at 10.5% ABV the fusel taste of alcohol was hidden behind the thick body and bitterness of the hops. A worthwhile contender in DIPA category.

Sweet cereal flavor, light body. Slight hop aroma of the noble variety. Large "Champagne like" bubbles. Crisp finish. A solid lager that takes no risks but doesnt disappoint. The quality that surprised me the most was the sweetness.
